Last summer's report that scientists may have been able to locate Higgs' boson caused a real shock - and not without cause.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not much.
Moreover, it is the last particle that was predicted in the Standard Model - our best, or, at least, the "least imperfect" description of nature and the behaviour of matter - but which could not have been detected in an experimental way before.
But physicists aren't quite sure it's the Higgs boson yet.
We know, without a shadow of doubt, that we're dealing with a really new particle and that it's a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
