Let's just say we're talking about the Higgs boson, because the odds of making a mistake seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is one law in this world that is entirely inevitable, saying that two things can't be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way around this rule, not even try too hard, or you'll hurt yourself.
But while particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the principle of Paulie's exclusion, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same moment in time if they are in the same "quantum state" - the "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Therefore, physics divides particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called farmmen who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, bosons, a vile band of anarchists, who have no respect for anything — at least this principle — may find themselves in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (by the way, quite extraordinary) Particle Adventure of Berkeley's Laboratory, these bosons are divided into two groups: mesons we're not going to talk about here, and power particles, which are the main forces of nature, and to which the Higgs boson is in some ways.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all exotic beings as one might think.
In fact, if you're able to read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly banal boson: photon, or "part of light", which is the "courier" of electromagnetic power.
Indeed, when a single particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "breaks" the electromagnetic field in this particular location, about as a stone thrown into the pond.
This "offence" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or UV, etc.) and this wave is nothing other than a photon - and therefore one of the "force transmitters" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the only difference that for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must have been violated.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to stimulate it, it is necessary to achieve very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond whose surface could shake only a very large stone.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator, like the one that operates at CERN, the Great Hadron Collider, which is a 27 km diameter ring, to achieve such enormous energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never hold on to the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who interact have mass, while others (as a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what could "can bring" all these researches ask Mrs. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the validity of the Standard Model (MP), and they also allow physicists to detect a discrepancy between observations and MM projections.
