The latter, it must be said, still has significant flaws, without offering any explanation for gravity (y!) or for dark matter that forms about 80 percent of the universe (ooh!).
But so far, no such discrepancies have been found at CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the daily life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that they do not exist.
See, early in the 1960s, pioneers of laser research in Bell's labs couldn't even imagine what revolution their work would cause.
They predicted their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist, Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell's Labs, where a laser was invented in 1960, and who himself designed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were impulsive) in 1962, said that the laser was initially viewed as more of a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
In addition, the application can be found for the tools that accompany the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his optical research in 1969.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, now serves as an eye for all digital cameras in the world and deserves the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
That certainly doesn't mean that Big Adron Collider's work is gonna change our lives, but it just shows, in fact, that everything can be.
