Completely opposite to the current exchange of money based on central banks numbered transactions between receiving parties with commissions to process them.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, there is clearly a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but converted to dollars, euros ...) and a protected BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows files to be exchanged between participants at the same level.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a payment facility.
The Bitcoin exchange rate, which reached a maximum of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing special compared to the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in the system in its virtual currency report published in October.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "like normal currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits" used to promote video games that are earned in the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
Facebook's social network has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations always control and process a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network function?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
Only for each new payment can the user choose another address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
