Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated actively in a number of Agency projects over the following years.
But Poland's journey to space started a lot earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always understood.
I would like to remind you, for example, of the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who, on 6 December 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his pioneering work "Introspection in Space".
The young engineer's ideas (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch Awards for "Introspection in Space".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned promoter of space, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway drone equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the draft.
It is not even clear whether a rocket should have been used to disperse or to brake the trolley.
Only the press of that era is aware of this threshing.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section in cooperation with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzycki.
The remaining material shows that the research has reached the practical test stage.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket, proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work of "Air Torpedo Missile and Aeroplane Bomb" by author Levy-Kivoblocsky came out.
Both projects were designed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczawy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended with the outbreak of war.
The following scientific work on space was published in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a reference to society in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problems, which publishes four long articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotović proposed the organization of a space society.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics ' Society (POA) has tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951), and as early as the autumn of the PAA became a valid member.
The following year, Kazimez Zarankevich, the first president of PAA, became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation (1902 - 1959).
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, which was capable of overcoming a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and had a weight of less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built and a two-stage RM-2 rocket was tested in the summer of 1959 on the Bled desert.
The rocket was about 1.4 metres long and had a weight of about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to carry out the actual scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could cross 14.5 km and its mission was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed to be two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (defined as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed and varied in size for scientific equipment.
Meteor-1A had an area of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C 0.62L.
All three types had a maximum flight range of 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, Meteor-2 was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2, with a start-up weight of 380 kg, was able to lift a 10 kg payload to a height of about 60 km.
The versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were then built.
Mention should also be made of Poland ' s accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR national committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Marioslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
