And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist in a nearby large business, says, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everyone has Internet, iPad, and electronic books.
No one ever voluntarily goes to these old-fashioned libraries anymore, right?
Peikenisse, a small-scale bedroom town under Rotterdam, has an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
In order to combat this unfortunate fact, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven fictional bridges, which are shown on euro bills, in the form of paint-painted iron concrete miniatures.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the city's fathers realized that they had the only chance to beat the statistics: to build a library here!
Vince Maas of the Rotterdamian Architectural Bureau MVRDV, a master of bold column diagrams and author of witty, sometimes even cynical, structures, took up the task with his usual unforgivability and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while members of the jury were perplexed and shrugged with their shoulders, the daring Maas folded out of his original gift a pyramid of size and completed the speech in defence of his project with the words, "Dear citizens!"
Here's my offer: Book Mountain in Speykenissa, the so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain grew at a cost of 30 million euros.
It is part of a renewal project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several surrounding dwellings and townships for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, "The Book Mountain" was awarded the second award for Best Library in the Netherlands 2012.
The project also participates in the National Dutch Woodwork Competition 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which had previously been unable to offer anything but a postmodern pedestrian area and a surprisingly ugly town hall whose white facade suggests a milk plant, has become richer than one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly, Speykenissa is the first public cultural building in the history of this town.
Long way to the book
The first impression is that Eldorado is booked under a cheese cap.
There's only one elevator going through the center of the mountain range, because the real fans of architecture and reading would prefer to explore this area on foot.
The room on all sides - bright and easily foreseeable - the floors of baked bricks and the elegant street lights are infalliblely creating a sense of public urban space.
The urban environment is being recreated perfectly.
The look is involuntarily looking for benches, dogs, and football boys and girls.
And there are books, books, books everywhere.
"The usual book shelves are along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark room, usually uncool and faceless," says Vini Maas.
We put a classic configuration of the space from the top to the head and pulled out the area to read from the outside.
The inner space of the book mountain has been well used, with offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental centre and technical facilities located in the centre.
The black book shelves, which serve as those walls, parapets, and stairways, are particularly encouraging.
Their kind, their texture, and their smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and construction engineers are lost in guesses, what kind of unknown material is this?
"We have sought to work with secondary materials," explains Jop Trauborst, the project manager representing the Speykenisse community, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once, at an agricultural enterprise in Frisland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fibrous material of millimetre thickness has been used as root pads.
It's cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons and can then be discarded.
For the library, this painting - for the first time in this volume - was pressed in a panel four centimeters thick.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbowplastics (KLP) becomes dark, homogeneous, solid material, smelling a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
They lead 105 steps to the top.
