Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role."
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, in doing so, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think she supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote to establish a no-flight zone.
As a result, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, moving from a policy that the US, to what it is said to have ruled, to a German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're just finding their part, but they're on their way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
The foreign policy followed by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position that is independent of the position of the US or European partners in its national interest.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests were very different from those of other large States, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the voting at the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to insult the public and elites in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to that, it's not completely one-sided.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Did Germany harm its relationship with the US by abstaining in important decisions such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are differing views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the United States clearly supported the veto.
Is there a divergence of views between the US and many European states?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government is deeply aware of the European position.
But with regard to the local political situation, the Government cannot, of course, take such a position openly.
I believe that the substantive differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is not very excited about Netanyahu politics.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the EU's most important partner on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, consistent European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and have to act instead on the basis of their own vision of the situation.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties to Israel.
The subject has always been sensitive.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany itself sees itself as an important international player, will it really take the lead?
Or is Germany still taking the lead hard?
Germany is not yet used to it; it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it has always been difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis — every time Germany takes an important role, there are a variety of anti-German feelings.
The Germans aren't just dealing with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much worse position than the US.
It must take into account the diversity of neighbours and opinions, which is not easy.
So the US's influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment, the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who's left?
The Germans will simply have to play a larger role.
Even if you don't like it, it's unpleasant, or it's making you feel bad, that's life!
Stephen Sabo, Deputy Director of the Trans-Atlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., where academics and political experts from Europe and North America work together on the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Protecting Trademarks" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is the world-famous brand, and Polo Ralph Lauren is also.
But what is Armani Polo?
It's a brand name that's officially registered in China that has nothing to do with the firms it's formed from.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names bring an action.
But it is also unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to defend their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer for Taylor Wessing, who specializes in trademark rights violations in the Far East.
There's a new case of this kind every week on my desk.
Simulators add just a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So Gucci makes Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German enterprises, such as the manufacturer of sports products Puma, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with records from the Trademark Registration Office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name that also uses the name of Ermenegildo Zegna's fashion house.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions of copying and infringement of intellectual property rights.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeits.
However, Pattloh's cases are not the same, and on instructions from his trustees, he is opposed to Chinese enterprises being granted the right to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Ban Minpai," a brand-passenger.
That word is associated with "ban dakuan."
That's what they call women who hunt rich men.
The Chinese authorities won't plead guilty.
"It hurts business, it needs to be fought," Pattloch is convinced.
"The brand is blurry, the unique position is lost, the image is suffering very much."
The financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are estimated at millions, especially in the case of expensive copies.
According to the CLSA Market Research Company, China, with a sales volume of Euro15 billion per year, is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is difficult and costly to remove questionable records in the trademark register.
The trial may last up to nine years, with unclear outcome.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed claims because after a long period of time, the disputed name became "market reality".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he will even have to pay the plagiarizer because he damaged his Chinese trademark, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also famous graphics cases.
In 2009, Daimler lost a lawsuit with the construction machine manufacturer Sony, a company that had recently acquired Putzmeister's concrete-sucking company.
Therefore, the Chinese still have the right to use a emblem similar to the Mercedes star.
Geely, who bought Volvo, originally used a blue-white logo similar to BMW; the process was successful, and Geely had to change it.
The manufacturer of fashion products, Lacoste, lost in China to simulations from Hong Kong and Singapore, whose famous crocodile looked the other way.
The Chinese authorities don't feel guilty.
The CTMO Trademark Registration Office in Beijing confirms that there were difficulties in 2010 owing to a shortage of staff and equipment.
But last year, there was a "return from an emergency in the working process to the norm".
Thus, the number of pending objections cases decreased by 22 per cent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were closed, 75 per cent more than last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending with the agency.
It's expensive to fight.
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
This record means that China has led the list of new registrations around the world for the tenth consecutive time, reporting to the agency.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion Yuan fees were paid.
If simplified, this means that each registration costs an average of 1,280 Yuan or 160 Euros.
It is worth many times more to challenge, as the case of the German family enterprise Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the Convergence has fought against a Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans were able to ensure that their illicit production of counterfeit car parts was eliminated.
However, the simulator has reserved Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
This was his own omission, as names in Germany are not protected, says Hanno Ventzler, Chairman of the Board of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the CTMO Trademark Registration Authority rejected the Munich claim.
True, in both of the following instances, Freudenberg won, but the other side is still fighting.
You need to be on your guard.
The matter is currently before the Supreme Court.
Ventzler hopes to bring the case to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says, "The process is extremely expensive and takes a lot of time, money, and nerves."
Domestic costs are unlikely to be accounted for, and the company's archives have had to look at even a hundred years ago to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg unsuccessfully offered the opposing side "a larger six-digit amount in euros" for a settlement.
"It's clear from here how much it costs us," Ventzler says.
The dangers of the Far East are threatening even Europe.
That is, if the simulators register unprotected trademarks there.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The Concern had long ceased production in those areas, but had been able to prevent registration.
