"I hope he'll be exactly the same president as the governor," says Oliver, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear most.
Bradley Manning hasn't complained of ill-treatment, pleads guilty.
The prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning ' s allegations of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning ' s stay in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires that the case be dismissed on the grounds that Manning's detention conditions were cruel.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment that he claimed he had been able to reschedule while in military prison.
During the cross-examination at the pre-trial hearing in Fort Meed, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that the weekly visits to Manning by the prison administration for nine months in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain any complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defence motion to dismiss Manning ' s case, on the grounds that his conditions of detention were cruel and sufficient in themselves, was conducted the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in custody.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is charged with the kidnapping of several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published online on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks' resources did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Fein, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been completed after Manning ' s visits by the administration during his stay in Quantico prison, where he was held under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he regarded the treatment of himself by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized".
The reports examined did not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manninga ' s direct question about his conditions of detention, Fein claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his verbal concern about those issues and that the authorities who visited him had discussed those problems with him and had stated that they would be dealt with but had not been recorded in writing.
"They recorded "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in conversation," Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a commission hearing on suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing several months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to be removed from the "trauma prevention" regime and reduced conditions of detention.
The military leadership explained that the limited regime of detention - lower than the one for suicide prevention - had been introduced for the protection of the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay to get them to cancel the injury prevention regime... so that my level of life could improve, from my point of view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thought of suicide in Kuwait and that he had once lost consciousness due to severe heat.
He explained that psychologically, it's very difficult when you're not allowed to know how your fate is being solved and what's happening in the outside world.
"My world has fallen to Camp Arifjan base, the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in this cage."
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - all alone.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to leave his mattress, blanket, slappers, a few clothes and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because sleeping, or even lying in the daytime, prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly struck by light from outside the cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turning over in bed at night, he said that he had been woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning ' s lawyer filed an official objection to Manning ' s ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manninga was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he had made during his testimony on Thursday that, after being forced to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico, he had been forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during the morning check.
Manning said he couldn't cover himself with a blanket during the test.
In response to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should leave a blanket that he could cover, but admitted that no one had explicitly ordered him to abandon him.
On Thursday, Manning stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not in danger.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a pair of underwear or slappers to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, his slappers and his glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had to endure during his detention and significantly reduce the sentence if Manning were found guilty by a military court, which was due to start his trial early next year.
The defence stated that it planned to invite Manning to confess guilt for less serious crimes and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The hearings are scheduled to resume this weekend, and it is expected that the prosecution will insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of detainees under the strictest possible regime.
Among the charges brought against Manning are complicity with the enemy, illegal facilitation of the release of data on the Internet, transmission of information relating to national defence and theft of State property or documents.
If he is convicted on all counts of the indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is a Mexican-American story.
