Old Battles in the New Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas can provide a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There have been familiar, meaningless debates about who started it; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time since the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip landed in the vicinity of the Israeli capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, while Israelis and Palestinians have been hopelessly caught up in their eternal conflict, the Middle East has been changed.
This may be seen in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have encircled many established realities in the rebel storm, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay away from the storm that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope that this deadly impasse will be overcome.
War without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire signed on 21 November were to be implemented, the clashes that took place this week only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement that took power in the Gaza Strip in 2007 will declare that they forced Israel to retreat despite its losses.
Despite the destruction of some faction leaders and the blockade of 1.7 million residents in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Indeed, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new, influential and rich friends.
The resurgent regional leader Turkey, once Israel ' s closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf States.
Hamas ' solemn supporters have claimed the establishment of an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by Hezbollah ' s paramilitary group to Syria, where increasingly Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad ' s power, to Jordan, where the King ' s authorities are threatening Hamas ' allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region took place on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country, in Egypt, where President Mohammed Mursi's influence was strengthened by the Muslim Brotherhood movement.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not focus on Hamas support.
On the contrary, the Muslim brothers are an organization much similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more likely to be populism.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice could not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, the supporters of the hard line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel's "Iron Dome" missile system has justified the cost of its development and successfully destroyed many of Hamas's rockets.
Israeli citizens can sleep in peace, at least for a while.
With regard to diplomacy, the US has remained faithful to its constant position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the beginning of the last round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel ' s economic prosperity, particularly under the Government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although some 30 Israelis had been killed since 2004 by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel had managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part through the wall that entered the West Bank of the Jordan River, a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protected Jewish settlements, which continued to expand despite the illegality of such acts under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, in preparation for the 22 January elections, has merged with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of condoning the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If they were given full power in the West Bank, would they not begin to launch rockets from there towards Israel, as their brothers in the Gaza Strip did?
It's better to keep them behind the wall and to suppress any attempts to lift their heads.
The hard-line supporters may win; however, their calculations may be rebutted in the Arab spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the most warm feelings for Israel, their domestic problems will be a priority.
Israel's defense budget is larger than all its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of war with the regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments to strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of President Mursi of Egypt, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must at least take into account the long-term effects of its policies.
As democratic changes take place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in the territories occupied by Israel, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Reprisals are already undermining the foundations of a democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic aspect, the growth of the Arab population, only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas have had to pay for the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external impulses.
There remains the only solution that the sane representatives on both sides continue to call for, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israel's concessions of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, which is not very impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which is long overdue in its decision to stop the flow of arms into the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, have a more favourable position than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the borders of the Jewish State adopted since 1967 in the light of the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more to create a Palestinian State than the forthcoming United Nations vote, which could result in recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never submitted his own peace plan.
After his return to the White House, he continues to show a reluctance to engage in a solution to the problem.
This is a catastrophic short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only if there is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australia has enacted the Uniform Cigarette Packaging Act.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of disease-affected body parts contrast in contrast with the sad green boxes that are the same for all cigarette stamps.
Australia ' s first worldwide uniform pack of cigarettes and tobacco law came into force, replacing logos and colouring different stamps with a similar box of dreary olives with creepy images of sick body parts and images of children whose health has been undermined by smoking.
In addition to the different images and inscriptions that warn of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between packs introduced from this Saturday is the names of stamps that are printed in the same small print.
These are the most difficult conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the aim of this measure is to keep young people from smoking by depriving them of this harmful habit of fashion.
This decision was based on studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 never became smokers in 99 out of 100 cases.
"It is clear that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey by packaging," explains Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown, for example, that the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess.
Australia was one of the countries with the lowest share of smokers in the world, so that those changes would not have a significant impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries were already considering doing so.
The tobacco industry was increasingly opposed to the adoption of the law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market where cheap and affordable cigarettes are sold.
"This law will lead to serious consequences different from what was intended by its initiators," says Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Counterfeit producers from China and Indonesia will supply much more such products for sale on the streets of Australia.
For someone, on the contrary, new laws encourage business growth.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family company, claims that the demand for portigars and silicone case files that conceal unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from zero) since two months ago, companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case in the high court of Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold some 6,000 products to wholesalers and is waiting for a new shipment.
It's a good business for us.
The potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures was, in the view of the experts, the popularity of social networks among the specific population targeted by those measures.
Following the enactment of a number of laws in Australia that have made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sports activities, and that prohibit sellers from placing cigarettes in a visible place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian Government has banned local companies and websites from posting advertising online, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
"If you're selling tobacco products and you only have this little loophole left, the idea of promoting your product on the Internet would seem very tempting to you," explains Becky Freeman, a public health research at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increasing number of reviews of brands written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he has spared no effort and time and made a video, or is it the advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco Australia claims that industry is now more busy adapting to new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry had even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: those States had submitted claims to the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade had been subject to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that all those countries ' trade relations with Australia were very small.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the Government had discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory smoke-awareness photographs.
This rule has now been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of strengthening laws is being considered in Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia have been defiantly disobeyed by innovation.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
"Just grab a cigarette and hide a pack in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on a pack.
To be honest, the only thing that can make me quit is my little girl.
James Yu, head of the tobacco store King of the Pack in central Sydney, claims that the same package made it difficult to place the goods on the shelves.
"I used to have an hour to unload my new shipment, and now four hours," he complains.
"The government had to take and ban cigarettes altogether, we'd say, what to do, okay, it's over, we close the store," he says, throwing his hands up.
