For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulphur to the top of the volcano on steep rock trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living from sulphur mining in the Kawah Idgen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day Anto goes down to the bottom of the crater, where the blue gas that comes up from the depths of the Earth is locked in contact with the air.
Huge pieces of sulphur, with a total weight of up to 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, pulls baskets on his shoulders and carries them up on a rocky rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, which is 2,386 metres high, it takes only 250 metres, but tired loaders take more than 40 minutes to climb a turtle's step, struggling to maintain balance and carefully finding the road so as not to stumble or fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rock a few years ago.
The cashiers from Kawah-Ijen earn 5 Euro cents per kilo of sulphur produced
When they get upstairs, they make their way between tourists who take pictures of them as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometres to the scales that the mining company has set up slightly higher, at an altitude of 1.850 metres.
This is PT Kandi Ngribi, an enterprise that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, better or worse, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) of petrochemical production, since this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"As the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about Rs. 46,000 (Euro3.8) for each walk," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to save Rs. 138,000 (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a miser for such an inhuman effort, it's three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wage for miners is very high by local standards, where coffee is paid Rs. 15,000 (Euro1.2) per day and the average monthly wage is Rs. 2 million (Euro167)," explains a freighter who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was Rs. 75,000 (Euro6.2) per day and the plot was not as heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a valid reason, which in Indonesia is as devastating as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are some Hindus, and brought her to Java to accept Islam."
Anto asthma, he can't breathe, he coughs all the time, and his eyes are gonna cry because of toxic gases.
