UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at UNASUR ' s VI ordinary meeting of Heads of State and Government, but sources from the Office and the President ' s Administration have indicated on the main page that it will be transmitted after the closure, but have confirmed that it will be published at some point on the Peruvian Government ' s website.
To questions about the text, they indicated that the contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Umala, during the press briefs.
Journalists ' access to Summit information was always limited.
In the course of the day, only a video of the Presidential Assembly without sound "closed session, no sound" was broadcast in the press room.
A small amount of information that was distributed among reporters was transmitted by the spokespersons of some UNASUR Governments present at the meeting, but not Peruvian.
The only document distributed during the day was a list of participating presidents, which caused the displeasure of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who requested more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian President's administration sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this is Umala's statement, not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was also not distributed, despite the press's insistence on doing so.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be checked that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities had tried to ensure that all journalists received transmission systems, but had limited information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the judgment of the International Court of Justice, which began hearing the statements of both parties in The Hague on Monday, as part of the indictment that Lima had brought against Santiago.
"We will observe and implement a decision that will clarify the differences that we now represent in this international court," said Umala, next to his Chilean colleague.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of differences, covenants and international tribunals", added Piñera, and welcomed the shaking of Umalu's hand against the background of the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would be subject to the International Court of Justice took place immediately after Colombia challenged this week the Bogotá Pact, according to which it recognized the submission to the verdicts of that international court following a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua, which it considered to be erroneous.
The summit was held in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Roussef; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership of UNASUR has been suspended since 2011, following impeachment by its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for opening the debate in the morning and closing the summit a little later in the afternoon of Lima time.
The Head of State read the outcome document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects among South American countries had been approved, with an estimated investment of $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residence agreements".
He reported that action was being taken to improve "cooperation against insecurity and organized transnational crime, to increase access to medicines, to affordable Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the cumulative and effective risks of natural disasters".
Since Europe in crisis, "the economic union (Latin America) should not have a triumphant foundation, but should serve to broaden our productive base and anticipate a better future for our cities", Umala added.
"We have decided to grant privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the link between South America's space, especially in the village and border areas... by uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes," said the Peruvian president in a message read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were from Peru and were limited to cross-axial axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve as a re-accession to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is now excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united and to have good relations among its neighbours, was another theme emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before participating in the regional meeting that he looked forward to meeting with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of an international court contested by Bogotá.
"The day after tomorrow (on Saturday), perhaps meet President Daniel Ortega," said Santos.
"We shall review all these ways, which are not mutually exclusive, including a pact with Nicaragua, will require discussion with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we can handle this as civilized and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they will have the presence of Enrique Peña Nieto, the new President of that country.
Also at the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met provisionally for the adoption of the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Chile, Guyana, Suriname, Paraguay, Uruguay and Venezuela form UNASUR, although the latter ' s participation has been suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
"South America should learn from Europe on the integration of citizenship": Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, has confirmed today that the creation of common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case, yes, should learn from Europe".
Correa, who participated in the VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) held in Lima, stated to State television in Peru that Europeans "killed each other during the Second World War" and in other clashes, "but now they are practically one homeland".
He defended, in this context, the South American Nationality Project, which is endorsed by the UNASUR countries.
"It is necessary to move citizens and workers freely across any South American country, as is already the case with members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want us back in time," he warned.
The Ecuadorian President has also shown himself to be a supporter of the renewal of the Organization of American States (OAS) on the premise that the influence of the Anglo-Saxon States should be reduced and that those who have signed the San José Pact on Human Rights should be taken into account.
Those who give lectures never make any commitments, and we South Americans, on the contrary, sign everything.
"It is inexplicable that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington and is funded by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum given by Ecuador to the founder of WikiLeaks, Juliana Assanju.
Correa assured that he did not regret this decision because he did not betray his principles with him, but respected his "deep values of democracy and human rights".
He added that, in due course, "there was some suspicion that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that the process would not be respected".
He also criticized Swedish justice for requiring him to come to his territory for questioning an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish law itself considers it possible to implement it by videoconference, which could be made available from the Embassy of Ecuador in London".
Correa confirmed that there was a risk that Assanj ' s physical and mental health would deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he arrived at our embassy, but the ambassador told me that he had a slight lung problem, nothing serious," said the Ecuadorian Head of State.
What really exists is the risk of his physical and mental deterioration due to being imprisoned in a small space without the ability to practice in the air.
"It affects the health of any human being," he added.
Correa indicated that the solution to the asylum issue granted to Assanju since June at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London, by providing a security of immunity that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, was in the hands of the United Kingdom, Sweden and the European judiciary, and stressed that there had been negotiations in London to find a solution to the problem of imprisonment of the founder of WikiLeaks.
We do not negotiate on human rights; we do not use that word here, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of the United Kingdom, Sweden and the European judiciary, because Assanja's lawyer, Balthazar Garson, has been conducting a number of trials in various European jurisdictions," he mentioned.
And he said, "If Britain offers a guarantee of immunity tomorrow, it will end."
And if Sweden, as it is perfectly permitted by its legislation and as it has done in other cases, interrogates Mr. Assange at the Embassy of Ecuador in London or interrogates him by Skype, the problem will be exhausted tomorrow.
Correa took the opportunity to act as a defender of freedom of the press and stressed that he did not tolerate "mediocreness, bad faith and lies that distort freedom of expression".
"The main enemies of freedom of the press are not spoiled political villains, but bad journalists who support profit, blackmail and extortion," he said.
In this regard, he was pleased that neither those journalists nor "neither bankers nor the bourgeois countries of the Hegemons dominate Ecuador" and added that, when re-elected, "it will deepen the revolution in order to continue its development in the right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to retain Paraguay's veto in UNASUR at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "should be firm and not tolerate opportunism and support for coups under the mask of legality", because in reality "it has destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian President also considered that the desire of his Colombian colleague, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua on maritime boundaries between the two countries, following the decision of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which was in favour of Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty, was "fully justified".
This decision has not yet been implemented.
This is a problem between the South American and Central American countries.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the desire to walk together.
They need to be processed together to overcome them and move forward.
He also expressed the hope that the maritime boundary dispute between Peru and Chile before the same court would be concluded well and said that "it is right for Latin America to resort to international bodies if the two countries commit themselves to a decision, however heavy it may be".
Regarding the possibility of standing as a candidate for the upcoming presidential election in Ecuador for a third consecutive term, he indicated that he was considering the possibility "with great optimism and joy, although sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost in the February 2013 elections, he would leave public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in unfair situations such as Ecuador, socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement felt that I was the one who guaranteed this likely victory, so I had to accept that responsibility," he said.
If I won, it would be my last term as president, and then we're out of public life.
If we lose, it's the same.
"It's a decision," he confirmed.
Correa also referred to the new treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke to Venezuelan Vice-President Nicholas Maduro, who told me that he was on his way to a treatment that was already scheduled, routine, and that he was expected to miss the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean that President Chávez's state of health is deteriorating," he explained.
