AIDS mortality today is the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was told that his AIDS test had yielded positive results.
"I've been stunned," he remembers the difficult moment, despite the doctor's tact, the moment.
The boy hid it from his family.
When he decided to deal with the disease on his own, he wanted to know as much about it as possible, and his efforts were justified -- he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the oldest HIV patients in Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he was admitted in 1994, and has overcome many obstacles.
He's been living with a diagnosis of "human immunodeficiency virus" (HIV) for 22 years.
So even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Protection clinic didn't want to say goodbye to him 'cause he had a cut.
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a sentence.
Now it is possible to survive the syndrome and do so without compromising the quality of life.
However, without knowing their disease, many people still come when the virus has already caused damage, "strengthen" their immune system, and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, "the greatest achievement so far is that the survival of a patient who begins treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", the head of HCG HIV, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, pointed out that this information was confirmed in a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
Infectionist and expert on HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, explained that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a sentence, but that life expectancy and quality of life depended on the extent to which patients had been affected by the immune system at the beginning of diagnosis, with better life expectancy for non-drug users: up to 30 years with 200 CD4 and up to 50 years when 500 CD4 were reported.
Simply put, the above means that someone who is diagnosed as HIV positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, "with control, can live without problems up to the age of 75", he explained.
In order to assess this progress, it should be remembered that Mexicans now have an average life expectancy of 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has declined from 6.678 in 2007 to 4.862 in 2011 (the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that 60 per cent of patients in the national database have died since the AIDS outbreak.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 deaths were recorded by May of this year; however, it is alleged that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I picture it, that's how things are at our hospital.
At least we haven't had a lack of medication in the last 12 years, the problem is that patients come very late because they don't know about their infected condition, that is, at the late stages of the disease.
He quoted the devastating data: "Nine of the 10 patients come when they already have some opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is diagnostics at an earlier stage, and it is therefore necessary to provide samples for detection on a mass scale, for all people who request it."
The proposal is shared by experts and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as by patients such as Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for testing, motivated only by the fact that his friend did so and despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS phase and even suffered from Kaposha sarcoa, a cancer that is a common complication.
Things change when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're gonna die, and they don't want to know.
"If I'm gonna die anyway, I'd rather get high three times a week," they say, but not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, I practice, I take medication.
To date, all his parents know is that he's had cancer.
I live a normal life like any other.
"I work, I have a lot of work, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I have a mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and another person," listed Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO in order to encourage those who are now in fear in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them be checked, if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, that's better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person who is responsible.
His message summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms at the counter
The gap between health programmes and a citizen is great, according to Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalahara, who has taken up the problem of HIV.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "in fact, the distribution of condoms has increased, we've been given one or two before, now we've been given hundreds of bags, and that's very good, but it turns out there are those who still don't have access to the condom," he said.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
"Why do you want them?" is a popular question, with ehidence and condemnation, by social workers, school counsellors, pharmacists and health workers who don't want to hear teenagers, assured propaganda.
I suggest that we change this inefficient distribution; that condoms are not just behind counters; and that hundreds of them be placed in vending machines in public toilets in places often visited by young people.
It's not a promotion of debauchery.
It was not about paying for beer and motel, but Governor Emilio González replied when asked if condoms could be distributed under his leadership.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who already practice sexual activity," he said.
Key data in Jalisco
A total of 13.435 cases (12.158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV) were registered.
The state ranks 4th in the national ranking for new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are in the sexual route, 6% in the blood and 2% in the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are between 4 and 5 people on one reported case who do not know about it.
